== Australian Market Context

=== Regulatory Environment

Derivatives use by superannuation funds in Australia is governed by:

- *APRA Prudential Standard SPS 530 (Investment Governance)*: Requires RSE licensees to have framework for derivative use, including policies on permitted instruments, risk limits, counterparty credit, and reporting
- *Corporations Act*: Requires derivatives be used consistent with fund's investment strategy and in members' best interests
- *ASIC Regulatory Guide 97*: Guidance on disclosing fees and costs including implicit costs of derivative strategies
- *AASB 9 Financial Instruments*: Accounting standard governing derivative valuation and hedge accounting
- *Your Future, Your Super*: Performance test compares investment returns including impact of derivatives/hedging

=== Market Dynamics

Australian superannuation funds collectively manage AU\$3.9 trillion (as of 2024), with significant derivative use for:
- *Currency hedging*: Most large funds hedge 30-70% of international equity exposure (which represents ~30% of typical fund portfolio)
- *Interest rate management*: Using swaps and futures to manage duration in AU\$1+ trillion fixed income allocations
- *Equity protection*: Put options and collar strategies during volatile markets
- *Alternatives hedging*: FX and interest rate hedges for infrastructure and property investments

Largest super funds (AustralianSuper AU\$300bn+, Australian Retirement Trust AU\$270bn+) have sophisticated in-house derivatives capabilities. Mid-sized funds may outsource some derivative management to asset consultants or fiduciary managers.

